---
import DocsLayout from '../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
---

<DocsLayout title="Introduction — unscripted/ui">
  <article>
    <header class="mb-2">
      <h1 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight">Introduction</h1>
      <p class="mt-1.5 max-w-[60ch] text-muted-foreground">
        shadcn-style components rebuilt on raw web platform primitives. Every interaction here —
        opening, closing, animating, positioning, dismissing — is HTML and CSS. The components
        ship zero JavaScript.
      </p>
    </header>

    <div class="docs-prose">
      <h2>Why this exists</h2>
      <p>
        This started as a simple question: how much of a modern component library survives with
        the script tag deleted? More than you'd expect. Recent platform work — the Popover API,
        invoker commands, anchor positioning, scroll-state queries, the customizable select —
        keeps absorbing jobs that used to belong to JavaScript. This site collects the results
        as a coherent set: each component is a copyable HTML fragment styled with Tailwind
        utilities on the same token contract shadcn/ui uses, so an existing shadcn theme works
        unchanged.
      </p>

      <h2>Browser support philosophy</h2>
      <p>
        Some components use features that are Baseline and boring (dialog, details, popover).
        Others use features that shipped in Chromium first (anchor positioning, customizable
        select, CSS carousels). The rule for everything here: <strong>the fallback must be
        functional</strong>. A select without <code>base-select</code> is the classic native
        select. A dropdown without anchor positioning opens centered. A carousel without
        scroll markers still scrolls. Each component page has a support table with the exact
        versions and the exact fallback behavior.
      </p>
      <p>
        The colored badges you see on component pages are <strong>live</strong> — they're
        rendered by <code>@supports</code> blocks, so they report on the browser you're using
        right now. No user-agent sniffing, no JS. One honest limitation: <code>@supports</code>
        can only test CSS, so HTML features like <code>commandfor</code> get a table row but no
        live badge.
      </p>

      <h2>Accessibility notes</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>
          Native elements ship their own semantics and keyboard behavior: dialog traps focus,
          details/summary announce as disclosures, radios give you arrow-key navigation.
          That's behavior JS libraries reimplement — here it's the browser's job.
        </li>
        <li>
          Where a pattern bends semantics, the component page says so out loud — see
          <a href="/components/tabs">Tabs</a>, which announces as a radio group and explains
          why that's the honest trade.
        </li>
        <li>
          Reduced motion is handled once, globally, in the token paste — every transition and
          animation in the library collapses to instant for users who ask for that.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2>What's deliberately missing</h2>
      <p>
        Some components genuinely still need JavaScript, and pretending otherwise would break
        the functional-fallback rule. Toasts need a timer and a queue. A combobox or command
        palette needs filtering — that's data work, not styling. Full ARIA
        <code>tablist</code>/<code>menu</code> semantics need roving focus management
        (<a href="/components/tabs">Tabs</a> and
        <a href="/components/dropdown-menu">Dropdown&nbsp;Menu</a> each explain the trade they
        make instead). When you need one of those, reach for a JS library without guilt — and
        keep shipping the zero-JS pieces for everything else.
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>
</DocsLayout>
